ents would close significant financial gaps that government cannot. Drawing on key contributions in economic sociology, social network theory, and economics, the book conceptualizes a collaborative model of investment that is already becoming increasingly common: Large investors contribute more directly to private market assets, while financial intermediaries seek to foster co-investment partnerships, better aligning incentives for all. A combination of rich case studies and rigorous theory enables asset owners to move toward more efficient, private-market investing, while also laying groundwork for research at the frontier of finance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aBusiness networks. 0aInstitutional investmentsxManagement. 0aInstitutional investors. 4aCollaborative model. 4aco-investment. 4afinancial intermediaries. 4ainfrastructure investment. 4ajoint ventures. 4along-term investment. 4aplatform companies. 4are-intermediation. 4areal assets. 4arelational contracts. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Finance / General.2bisacsh1 aSharma, Rajiv, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSinclair, Duncan L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503602755zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503602755423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503602755.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles